{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"HTML with CSS Integration","slug":"html-css-integration","subject":"HTML","category":"Web Development","level":"Advanced","estimated_read_time":"15 minutes","prerequisites":["HTML Attributes"],"learning_objectives":["Three ways to add CSS (Inline, Internal, External)","Load order and cascading rules","Linking fonts"],"theory":"# Integration with CSS\n\nHTML provides structure. CSS provides style. There are 3 ways to integrate them.\n\n## 1. Inline CSS\nUse the `style` attribute.\n*   **Pros:** Quick fix.\n*   **Cons:** Hard to maintain, no reuse.\n```html\n<h1 style=\"color:blue;\">Hello</h1>\n```\n\n## 2. Internal CSS\nUse the `<style>` tag in `<head>`.\n*   **Pros:** Single file.\n*   **Cons:** Can't share styles between pages.\n```html\n<head>\n<style>\n  h1 { color: blue; }\n</style>\n</head>\n```\n\n## 3. External CSS (Best Practice)\nLink to a `.css` file.\n*   **Pros:** Share styles across 1000s of pages. Cacheable.\n```html\n<link rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"styles.css\">\n```\n\n## The `<link>` Tag\n*   `rel=\"stylesheet\"`: Relationship.\n*   `href`: Path to file.\n\n## Other Integrations\n*   **Google Fonts:** Linked via `<link>`.\n*   **Favicons:** Linked via `<link rel=\"icon\">`.","syntax":"<link rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"style.css\">","examples":[{"code":"<head>\n  <link rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"main.css\">\n  <link rel=\"icon\" href=\"favicon.ico\">\n</head>","output":"Links styles and icon.","explanation":"Standard setup."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Wrong file path","correction":"If styles don't load, 99% of time the href path is wrong (e.g., css/style.css vs style.css).","example":"Check console for 404."},{"mistake":"Using inline styles","correction":"Avoid style='...'. Always use classes.","example":"❌ <p style> ✅ <p class>"}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"What is the priority order of CSS?","difficulty":"Easy","answer":"Inline Style > Internal/External (depending on order) > Browser Default. (Exceptions include !important)."},{"question":"What is the relation between HTML and CSS?","difficulty":"Easy","answer":"HTML defines the DOM elements. CSS targets those elements via selectors (tag, class, id) to apply visual properties."}],"practice_problems":[{"difficulty":"Beginner","problem":"Link a stylesheet named 'theme.css' located in a 'css' folder.","hint":"href='css/theme.css'","solution":"<link rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"css/theme.css\">"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"Theming","description":"Websites change themes (Dark/Light) just by swapping the linked CSS file or changing a class on the HTML body.","code":"document.body.classList.toggle('dark')"}],"exam_notes":["External CSS is best <link>","Internal CSS in <style>","Inline CSS in style attribute (Avoid)","Link goes in <head>"],"summary":"HTML without CSS is ugly. The <link> tag allows you to attach external stylesheets, enabling you to control the look and feel of your entire website from a single file. This separation of concerns is the gold standard of web development.","order":37},"courseTutorials":[{"slug":"html-document-structure","path":"content/html/html-document-structure.json","title":"HTML Document Structure","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":2},{"slug":"html-comments","path":"content/html/html-comments.json","title":"HTML Comments","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":3},{"slug":"html-editors","path":"content/html/html-editors.json","title":"HTML Editors & Tools","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":4},{"slug":"html-elements","path":"content/html/html-elements.json","title":"HTML Elements","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":5},{"slug":"html-attributes","path":"content/html/html-attributes.json","title":"HTML Attributes","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":6},{"slug":"html-audio-video","path":"content/html/html-audio